>>b45720e1-3884-4328-a831-0cdc2ce039dd
People want liberty within their in-group, but individuals cannot complete against collectives. 

So there is an aesthetic societal sweet spot where there's liberty, but only within the in-group, yet enough unity among individuals to enable competition as a collective.  

The goal is success  for 'us',  not abdication of collective agency to the whims of the universe.  People sometimes feel instinctively that liberty is a powerful means to success.    

The universe will favor collectives that strive to continue.  This success will be at the expense of the liberty of individuals outside those collectives first, and often, even unnecessarily, also for members of those very (ugly and oppressed) collectives as well.

Libertarians should strive to keep the collective they strive as a member of as free as possible while making allowances for their social unit to be sufficiently unified to be competitive among other collectives.  Liberty is an aesthetic ideal.  We like it because it offers opportunity we think.  There are competitive benefits to liberty as well that mean collectives that provide liberty for their members may compete successfully against collectives that trade all their individual members' liberty for unity.  

But success is not a liberty cargo cult.  You can't just liberty and count on success to magically appear because that ideal is somehow blessed by the stars.   Competition is always happening between collectives as well as between individuals.  The universe is not biased as to who prevails, life merely poses the question and the living strive to exhibit the answer.

To see this the value of collective unity, just look at the collectivism in eusocial beings and among cells and even in units like dog-packs.  There are situations where collectivism is good.

However individuals can evolve faster than collectives.  This is the competitive advantage in liberty.  Bacteria become resistant to antibiotics, but we multicelluar humans aren't yet resistant to cyanide.

>>76b1c4a9-4f55-4dc9-be91-c7dfd1fd79ca
Yes.  Thanks, and it is comfy.

The only weakness ( which I admit this place hasn't grown to need yet, but hopefully will ) is some kind of way to leverage the moderation done by other users in a way that doesn't  let them impose their opinions on users.

What I was thinking is have a way for users to publish their blacklists, and have blacklists automatically composed of other users' blacklists.  Maybe there could be a weighting system where you assign a weight of .5 to someone's blacklist and it cuts the probablity in half that one of the things they blacklisted are shown.  Maybe have an icon that says:This item was blacklisted by subscription (only when the post is shown) and have a dropdown saying which list blacklisted it.  If someone repeatedly blacklists good stuff you blacklist their blacklist ( or just unsubscribe ).   You would  want it to be probabilistic so you can monitor abuse by the people you subscribe to.  Maybe cap it at .5 to force everyone to contribute to the metamoderation.

Better to firewall all traffic to go over Tor, and use regular firefox on this site, keeping a virgin Tor Browser.    Perhaps it would be worth running firefox  with firejail or something, but they seem to have built some of that functionality in, so it may be unneccessary.

You don't want to be poking holes in TorBrowser with 'mitigations'.   Really if you need TorBrowser you probably should be using tails anyway.  Keep TorBrowser for when you want to escape your persistent tor id.
